# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: graph-database
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Cypher was largely an invention of Andrés Taylor while working for Neo4j, Inc.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Cypher was originally intended to be used with the graph database Neo4j, but was opened up through the openCypher project in October 2015.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] The language was designed with the power and capability of SQL (standard query language for the relational database model) in mind, but Cypher was based on the components and needs of a database built upon the concepts of graph theory.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] In a graph model, data is structured as nodes (vertices in math and network science) and relationships (edges in math and network science) to focus on how entities in the data are connected and related to one another.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Cypher is based on the Property Graph Model, which organizes data into nodes and edges (called “relationships” in Cypher).
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] In addition to those standard graph elements of nodes and relationships, the property graph model adds labels and properties for describing finer categories and attributes of the data.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] They can hold any number of attributes (key-value pairs) called properties.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Nodes can be tagged with zero or more labels (like tags or categories), representing their different roles in a domain.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Relationships provide directed, named, semantically-relevant connections between two node entities.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] A relationship always has a direction, a start node, an end node, and exactly one relationship type.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Like nodes, relationships can also have properties.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Labels can group similar nodes together by assigning zero or more node labels.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Labels are kind of like tags and allow you to specify certain types of entities to look for or create.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Properties are key-value pairs with a binding of a string key and some value from the Cypher type system.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Cypher queries are assembled with patterns of nodes and relationships with any specified filtering on labels and properties to create, read, update, delete data found in the specified pattern.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] The Cypher's data type system includes many of the common data types used in other programming and query languages.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Supported data types include scalar value types such as boolean, string, number, integer, and floating-point numbers.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] It also supports temporal types like `datetime`, `localdatetime`, date, time, localtime, and duration.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Container data types for maps and lists are available, along with graph types for node, relationship, path, and a void type.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] The Cypher query language depicts patterns of nodes and relationships and filters those patterns based on labels and properties.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Cypher’s syntax is based on ASCII art, which is text-based visual art for computers.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] This makes the language very visual and easy to read because it both visually and structurally represents the data specified in the query.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] For instance, nodes are represented with parentheses around the attributes and information regarding the entity.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Relationships are depicted with an arrow (either directed or undirected) with the relationship type in brackets.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Similar to other query languages, Cypher contains a variety of keywords for specifying patterns, filtering patterns, and returning results.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Among those most common are: MATCH, WHERE, and RETURN.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] These operate slightly differently than the SELECT and WHERE in SQL; however, they have similar purposes.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] MATCH is used before describing the search pattern for finding nodes, relationships, or combinations of nodes and relationships together.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] WHERE in Cypher is used to add additional constraints to patterns and filter out any unwanted patterns.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Cypher’s RETURN formats and organizes how the results should be outputted.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Just as with other query languages, you can return the results with specific properties, lists, ordering, and more.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] The WHERE clause then filters to only keep patterns where the Movie node in the match clause has a year property that is less than the value of the parameter passed in.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] In the return, the query specifies to output the movie nodes that fit the pattern and filtering from the match and where clauses.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Cypher also contains keywords to specify clauses for writing, updating, and deleting data.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] CREATE and DELETE are used to create and delete nodes and relationships.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] SET and REMOVE are used to set values to properties and add/delete labels on nodes.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] MERGE is used to create nodes uniquely without duplicates.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Nodes can only be deleted when they have no other relationships still existing.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] With the openCypher project, an effort began to standardize Cypher as the query language for graph processing.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] As part of this process there have been five face-to-face openCypher Implementers Meetings (oCIMs).
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] The first meeting took place in February 2017 at SAP's headquarters in Walldorf in Germany, coincident with a meeting of the Linked Data Benchmark Council.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] The most recent OCIM took place in Berlin, coincident with the W3C Workshop on Web Standards for Graph Data Management, in March 2019.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] At that meeting, there was a consensus to work towards Cypher becoming a significant input into a wider project for an international standardized Graph Query Language called GQL.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] In September 2019, a proposal for a GQL standard project was approved by a vote of national standards bodies which are members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1 (responsible for information technology standards).
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] As of 2024, the GQL Standard has been published as the standard graph query language under ISO/IEC 39075:2024.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] The first open-source implementation of a subset of the language is already available.
[src:graph-database/cypher-query-language] Aside from the implementation, one can also find a formalization and read the syntax of the specific subset of GQL.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:graph-database/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:graph-database/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:graph-database/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:graph-database/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:graph-database/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:graph-database/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] In the field of database design, a **multi-model database** is a database management system designed to support multiple data models against a single, integrated backend.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] In contrast, most database management systems are organized around a single data model that determines how data can be organized, stored, and manipulated.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Document, graph, relational, and key–value models are examples of data models that may be supported by a multi-model database.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] The relational data model became popular after its publication by Edgar F.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Due to increasing requirements for horizontal scalability and fault tolerance, NoSQL databases became prominent after 2009.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] NoSQL databases use a variety of data models, with document, graph, and key–value models being popular.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] A multi-model database is a database that can store, index and query data in more than one model.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] For some time, databases have primarily supported only one model, such as: relational database, document-oriented database, graph database or triplestore.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] A database that combines many of these is multi-model.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] This should not be confused with multimodal database systems such as Pixeltable or ApertureDB, which focus on unified management of different media types (images, video, audio, text) rather than different data models.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] For some time, it was all but forgotten (or considered irrelevant) that there were any other database models besides relational.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] The relational model and notion of third normal form were the default standard for all data storage.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] However, prior to the dominance of relational data modeling, from about 1980 to 2005, the hierarchical database model was commonly used.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Since 2000 or 2010, many NoSQL models that are non-relational, including documents, triples, key–value stores and graphs are popular.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Arguably, geospatial data, temporal data, and text data are also separate models, though indexed, queryable text data is generally termed a "search engine" rather than a database.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] The first time the word "multi-model" has been associated to the databases was on May 30, 2012 in Cologne, Germany, during the Luca Garulli's key note "*NoSQL Adoption – What’s the Next Step?*".
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Luca Garulli envisioned the evolution of the 1st generation NoSQL products into new products with more features able to be used by multiple use cases.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] The idea of multi-model databases can be traced back to Object–Relational Data Management Systems (ORDBMS) in the early 1990s and in a more broader scope even to federated and integrated DBMSs in the early 1980s.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] An ORDBMS system manages different types of data such as relational, object, text and spatial by plugging domain specific data types, functions and index implementations into the DBMS kernels.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] A multi-model database is most directly a response to the "polyglot persistence" approach of knitting together multiple database products, each handing a different model, to achieve a multi-model capability as described by Martin Fowler.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] This strategy has two major disadvantages: it leads to a significant increase in operational complexity, and there is no support for maintaining data consistency across the separate data stores, so multi-model databases have begun to fill in this gap.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Multi-model databases are intended to offer the data modeling advantages of polyglot persistence, without its disadvantages.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Operational complexity, in particular, is reduced through the use of a single data store.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] As more and more platforms are proposed to deal with multi-model data, there are a few works on benchmarking multi-model databases.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] For instance, Pluciennik, Oliveira, and UniBench reviewed existing multi-model databases and made an evaluation effort towards comparing multi-model databases and other SQL and NoSQL databases respectively.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] 2. they can employ a unified query language such as AQL, Orient SQL, SQL/XML, SQL/JSON to retrieve correlated multi-model data, such as graph-JSON-key/value, XML-relational, and JSON-relational in a single platform.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] 3. they are able to support multi-model ACID transactions in the stand-alone mode.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] The main difference between the available multi-model databases is related to their architectures.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Multi-model databases can support different models either within the engine or via different layers on top of the engine.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Some products may provide an engine which supports documents and graphs while others provide layers on top of a key-key store.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] With a layered architecture, each data model is provided via its own component.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] In addition to offering multiple data models in a single data store, some databases allow developers to easily define custom data models.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] This capability is enabled by ACID transactions with high performance and scalability.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] In order for a custom data model to support concurrent updates, the database must be able to synchronize updates across multiple keys.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] ACID transactions, if they are sufficiently performant, allow such synchronization.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] JSON documents, graphs, and relational tables can all be implemented in a manner that inherits the horizontal scalability and fault-tolerance of the underlying data store.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] The traditional theory of relations is not enough to accurately describe multi-model database systems.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Recent research is focused on developing a new theoretical foundation for these systems.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] Category theory can provide a unified, rigorous language for modeling, integrating, and transforming different data models.
[src:graph-database/multi-model-database] By representing multi-model data as sets and their relationships as functions or relations within the Set category, we can create a formal framework to describe, manipulate, and understand various data models and how they interact.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] It is most known for creating the Neo4j Graph database, a graph database management system (GDBMS), which is implemented in Java and accessible from software written in other languages using the Cypher query language through a transactional HTTP endpoint, or through the binary "Bolt" protocol.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] The company contributed to the development of the Graph Query Language (GQL), an ISO-standardized query language for property graphs, and is a founding member of the GraphQL Foundation, an open-source initiative under the Linux Foundation.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Graph database management systems, such as the Neo4j Graph Database, are used in artificial intelligence applications to represent and query relationships within connected data.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] As of 2024, the company was valued at $2.2 billion with over 800 employees and 1,700 customers globally, with deployments across financial institutions, government, retailers, and technology companies.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j has over 300 enterprise customers, including Adobe, Microsoft, Walmart, UBS, and Daimler Truck.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j is developed by Neo4j, Inc., headquartered in San Mateo, California, United States, with locations in Sweden, Germany, the United Kingdom, France, Singapore, and Australia.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] The company was founded in 2007 in Sweden as an open source project by Emil Eifrem, Johan Svensson, and Peter Neubauer, but the idea for the company dates back to a drawing Eifrem sketched on the back of his napkin during a flight in 2000.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j was developed as an alternative to traditional tabular databases for use cases in which data relationships are central to the structure and querying of information.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] It is used in applications such as AI systems, recommendation engines, fraud detection, supply chain, and pharmaceutical research, where traversing relationships between data points is a requirement.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] The name combines "Neo," meaning "new," with "4j," a naming convention in the Java community meaning "for Java." The project was originally called “Project Neo,” and the name Neo4j was adopted when the company was formed.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] The company helped popularize the term “graph database,” thus creating a new market category.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2011, the company relocated to Silicon Valley, while its engineering hub remained in Sweden.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2016, the Neo4j graph database was used in the analysis of the Panama Papers, a data leak that exposed how wealthy individuals and organizations used offshore financial structures to manage and conceal assets.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2017, NASA acknowledged Neo4j’s contribution to Project Orion for its use in retrieving missing data from the Apollo program.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2018, the company launched its Graphs4Good program to support social impact and non-corporate use cases.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Neo4j supported vaccine product development.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j surpassed $200 million in revenue in 2024, and in 2025, it was reported that 84 of the Fortune 100 and over half of the Fortune 500 use Neo4j’s software to build, orchestrate, and deploy graph databases, including in AI systems at Uber, Walmart, and Daimler Truck.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2025, Neo4j announced a $100 million investment in generative AI, including a startup program supporting 1,000 AI-focused companies worldwide; program members include Medium, Shutl (acquired by eBay), and SOUQ (acquired by Amazon).
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2026, the company announced its acquisition of GraphAware, an intelligence analysis software provider for government agencies, as part of its AI investment.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j participates in the AI Alliance and engages with Linux Foundation projects focused on open-source data and AI ecosystems.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j raised $10.6 million in Series A Funding led by Fidelity Growth Partners Europe in 2011.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In November 2012, the company raised $11 million in Series B Funding led by Sunstone Capital.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In January 2015, Neo4j secured $20 million in Series C Funding led by Creandum and Dawn Capital.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In November 2016, Neo4j secured $36 million in Series D Funding led by Greenbridge Partners Ltd.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In November 2018, Neo4j secured $80 million in Series E Funding led by One Peak Partners and Morgan Stanley Expansion Capital, with participation from other investors including Creandum, Eight Roads and Greenbridge Partners.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In June 2021, Neo4j announced $325 million in Series F funding, led by Eurazeo and GV (Alphabet’s venture capital arm), which valued the company at over $2 billion making the company one of the best funded database companies.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In late 2024, the company began preparations for an initial public offering (IPO) on the Nasdaq stock exchange.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] By early 2025, the company announced it had surpassed $200 million in Annual Recurring Revenue (ARR).
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2026, the company continues to maintain its position as the most widely deployed graph database, according to industry rankings, while remaining IPO-ready as market conditions for tech listings stabilize.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j released version 1.0 of its graph database in 2010, version 2.0 in 2013, version 3.0 in 2016, version 3.5 in 2018, aimed at AI and machine learning, and version 4.0 in 2020 with unlimited scaling, partitioning, also known as ‘sharding,’ and role-based access.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2022, version 5.0 of its graph database was released.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j launched Ops Manager, a tool to monitor and manage global deployments in a unified dashboard in 2022, and vector search to its graph database in 2023, expanding contextual search for generative AI and large language models.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In 2025, the company launched agentic AI enterprise offerings; Neo4j Aura Agent lets companies build, test, and deploy AI agents using their enterprise data, providing end-to-end automated orchestration and AIOps for graph-based knowledge retrieval.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j also launched Aura Graph Analytics for cloud data warehouses and data lake platforms, including Oracle, Microsoft SQL and OneLake, Databricks, Snowflake, and Google BigQuery.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In September 2025, Neo4j introduced Infinigraph, a scalable graph database architecture designed for operational, analytical and AI workloads at over 100 terabytes and billions of nodes.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In March 2024, Neo4j and Microsoft announced a collaboration to integrate graph database capabilities into Azure AI services, including Fabric and Azure OpenAI.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] The integration lets users build knowledge graphs, supporting AI use cases such as GraphRAG.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] In June 2024, Neo4j integrated with Snowflake to enable graph analytics and machine learning directly within the Snowflake AI Data Cloud, allowing users access to 65 graph algorithms using SQL.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j has multiple editions for both its self-managed and fully managed offerings.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] As an ACID-compliant transactional database with native graph storage and processing, Neo4j graph database is available in three editions: Community Edition, Enterprise Edition, and Infinigraph Edition.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Community Edition is free and open source software under the GNU General Public License version 3 (GPLv3).
[src:graph-database/neo4j] The Enterprise and Infinigraph Editions are distributed under a closed-source commercial license and includes additional features related to scalability, performance, operability, and security.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] The previous licensing of Enterprise Edition was dual-licensed: GPL v3 (with parts of the code under AGPLv3 with Commons Clause), allowing for clustering, hot backups, and monitoring.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j AuraDB is available in four tiers: Free, Professional, Business Critical, and Virtual Dedicated Cloud.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] The data elements Neo4j stores in its graph database are nodes, edges which connect nodes to one another, and attributes of nodes and edges.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] As of version 2.0, indexing was added to Cypher with the introduction of schemas.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Previously, indexes were supported separately from Cypher.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Database researcher Andy Pavlo from Carnegie Mellon University has questioned graph databases' decision to abandon the longstanding relational model in favor of a custom model.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Researchers from CWI benchmarked a modified version of DuckDB against Neo4j on graph-related workloads and found that, despite being an extension of a relational database running SQL, their implementation outperforms Neo4j in a few specific tasks.
[src:graph-database/neo4j] Neo4j sued PureThink, for utilizing a power created under the terms of the GNU AGPL, to remove a restrictive Commons clause that Neo4j had added to the AGPL license.
[src:graph-database/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:graph-database/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:graph-database/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:graph-database/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:graph-database/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:graph-database/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:graph-database/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:graph-database/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:graph-database/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:graph-database/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:graph-database/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:graph-database/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:graph-database/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:graph-database/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:graph-database/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:graph-database/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:graph-database/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:graph-database/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:graph-database/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:graph-database/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:graph-database/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:graph-database/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:graph-database/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:graph-database/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:graph-database/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:graph-database/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:graph-database/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:graph-database/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:graph-database/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:graph-database/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:graph-database/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:graph-database/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:graph-database/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
